  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering in several key ways:\n\n1. Global Standards and Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Egmont Group collaboration between financial intelligence units\n\n2. Legal Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Extradition agreements\n- Information sharing protocols\n- Common reporting standards\n- Coordinated investigations and prosecutions\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Cross-border financial monitoring\n- Asset freezing and seizure mechanisms\n\n4. Enforcement Dimensions\n- Harmonization of criminal definitions\n- Standardized investigative techniques\n- International cooperation in prosecution\n- Shared intelligence and evidence gathering\n\n5. Regulatory Approaches\n- Consistent risk assessment methodologies\n- Uniform banking transparency requirements\n- Aligned anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks\n- Coordinated financial sanctions\n\n6. Technological Considerations\n- Digital transaction tracking\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Cybercrime prevention\n- International data exchange platforms\n\nThese intersections create complex, multilayered legal and regulatory environments addressing money laundering prevention globally.",
